0015.jpg 8r 15 JS Aug 11, 2012 The problem of finding a circle touching two given points and a given line is here called the 'Problema naupegicum', though it is not clear from these pages exactly how this problem is relevant to ship-building. Harriot notes that he has met the problem elsewhere, in the pages of Pappus, Book 7, where it is attributed to Apollonius. It seems that at this time Harriot was not yet as familiar with the work of Apollonius as he later became. For much more work on this and related problems, see his notes on Viète's Apollonius Gallus (1600). Observe that where Harriot moves into formal mathematics he also begins to write in Latin. Problema Naupegicum
0015.jpg 8r 15 JS Aug 11, 2012 Problema Naupegicum Hinc problema unum Appoloniacum , de quo mentionem facit Pappus lib. 7. ex. lib. Appol. pa. 159. This problem is an Apollonian one, solved, of which mention is made in Pappus, Book 7, on the Book of Apollonius, page 159.
0015.jpg 8r 15 JS Aug 11, 2012 Problema Naupegicum Datis duobus punctis et linea: circulum, illa tria contingentem, describere. Given two points and line, to draw a circle touching those three.
0015.jpg 8r 15 JS Aug 11, 2012 Problema Naupegicum Puncta data: $ b $, $ e $ linea data $ cd $ interminata. The given points, $ b $, $ e $; the given line $ cd $, continued indefinitely.
0015.jpg 8r 15 JS Aug 11, 2012 Problema Naupegicum Quæritur: punctum contactus $ h $. Sought is the point of contact, $ h $.
0015.jpg 8r 15 JS Aug 11, 2012 Problema Naupegicum cæteri casus possibiles et impossibiles facile intelligantur vide alteram paginam. Other cases, possible and impossible, are easily understood, see the other page.
0015.jpg 8r 15 JS Aug 11, 2012 Problema Naupegicum $ bi $ et $ ie $ datis, $ be $ nota erit. Igitur $ hs $ est media proportionalis inter $ bs $ et $ es $, et nota centrum $ A $ erit in concursum perpendicularium $ hA $ et $ fA $. Dabuntur etiam $ ch $ et $ hd $. vel $ il $ et $ le $. $ il = le $. quia $ Ale $ rectus. In triangulo $ etb $ dantur duo latera et angulus $ teb $; ergo omnia latera et $ Ah $ semidiameter peripheriæ circumscribentis dabuntur in numeris canonis per doctrinam triangulorum, et etiam in partibus $ bc $ primo datis. If $ bi $ and $ ie $ are given, $ be $ will be known. Therefore $ hs $ is the mean proportional between $ bs $ and $ es $, and the known centre $ A $ will be at the metting point of the perpendicular $ hA $ and $ fA $. Also $ ch $ and $ hd $ are given, or $ il $ and $ le $; and $ il = le $ because $ Ale $ is a right angle. In the triangle $ etb $ there are given two lines and the angle $ teb $; therefore all the sides and $ Ah $, the semidiameter of the circumscribed circumference are given in tabulated numbers by the doctrine of triangles, and also in terms of $ bc $, given at the beginning.

Datis duobus punctis intra peripheriam circuli: per illa puncta et terminos Diametri circuli dati, peripheriam circuli ducere. Given two points inside the circumference of a circle, through those points and the ends of the diameter of the given circle, draw the circumference of a circle.
0019.jpg 10r 19 JS Aug 15, 2012 Problema Appolonicum aliud. vide Pappum. lib. 7. pag. 159. Another problem of Apollonius, see Pappus, Book 7, page 159. Data. $ a $. $ b $. puncta. Given, the points $ a $, $ b $.
0019.jpg 10r 19 JS Aug 15, 2012 Problema Appolonicum aliud. vide Pappum. lib. 7. pag. 159. Another problem of Apollonius, see Pappus, Book 7, page 159. Ex ista constructione cæteri casus facile intelligantur. From this construction, other cases are easily understood.
0019.jpg 10r 19 JS Aug 15, 2012 Problema Appolonicum aliud. vide Pappum. lib. 7. pag. 159. Another problem of Apollonius, see Pappus, Book 7, page 159. Usus in planisphæ- rio ptolomaico. Used in the planisphere of Ptolemy.
0019.jpg 10r 19 JS Aug 15, 2012 Problema Appolonicum aliud. vide Pappum. lib. 7. pag. 159. Another problem of Apollonius, see Pappus, Book 7, page 159. Sit iam factum. Et peripheria circuli transiens per data puncta sit $ abch $ cuius centrum $ g $. Et $ cfe $ diameter circuli dati. a punctis $ a $ et $ b $ datis ducuntur per centrum $ f $, $ afh $ et $ bfm $. Rectangulum ex $ cf $ et $ fe $; hoc est quadratum ex $ fe $, æquantur rectangulo ex $ af $ et $ fh $; vel $ bf $ et $ fm $. Ergo $ fe $ est media proportionalis inter $ af $ et $ fh $. Suppose it already done. And let the circumference of the circle passing through the given points be $ abch $, whose centre is $ g $. And $ cfe $ is the diameter of the given circle. From the given points $ a $ et $ b $ there are drawn through the centre $ f $, the lines $ afh $ and $ bfm $. The product of $ cf $ and $ fe $, that is, the square of $ fe $, is equal to the product of $ af $ and $ fh $, or of $ bf $ and $ fm $. Therefore $ fe $ is the mean proportional between $ af $ and $ fh $.
0019.jpg 10r 19 JS Aug 15, 2012 Problema Appolonicum aliud. vide Pappum. lib. 7. pag. 159. Another problem of Apollonius, see Pappus, Book 7, page 159. Problema igitur perficitur ad hunc modum. A punctis datis $ a $ et $ b $ ducantur rectæ ad centrum $ f $. $ af $ et $ bf $. ad $ af $ et a puncto $ f $, sit $ fd $ perpendicularis, ut ducatur recta $ ad $. et a puncto $ d $ erigatur perpendicularis $ do $. producatur $ af $ et concurret cum $ do $ in puncto $ h $. a medio $ ah $ fit perpendicularis $ ig $ et a mdeio $ ab $ sit perpendicularsi $ kr $. secabit $ iq $ in puncto $ g $. quod est centrum peripheriæ quæsitæ. demonstratio manifesta ex propertate superius allata. &c. The problem is therefore brought about in this way. From the given points $ a $ et $ b $ there are drawn the lines $ af $ and $ bf $ to the centre $ f $. Let $ fd $ be perpendicular to $ af $ at the point $ f $, so that there is drawn the line $ ad $. And form the point $ d $ there is erected the perpendicular $ do $. The line $ af $ is extended and meets $ do $ in the point $ h $. From the middle of $ ah $ there is constructed the perpendicular $ ig $, and from the middle of $ ab $ the perpendicular $ kr $ will cut $ iq $ in the point $ g $, which is the centre of the sought circumference. The demonstration is clear from the property reported above. etc.
0019.jpg 10r 19 JS Aug 15, 2012 Problema Appolonicum aliud. vide Pappum. lib. 7. pag. 159. Another problem of Apollonius, see Pappus, Book 7, page 159. Si dentur $ ab $, $ af $, $ bf $, et $ ce $ in numeris; Dabuntur etiam in iisdem $ ig $ et $ kg $ nam angulus $ bah $ cogitus est ex data triangulo $ abf $. Dantur $ ab $ et $ ah $. notum igitur $ bh $. et diameter circumscribentis peripheriæ per doctrinam triangulorum. &c. If there are given $ ab $, $ af $, $ bf $, and $ ce $ in numbers, there will be given also in the same way $ ig $ and $ kg $, for the angle $ bah $ is known from the given triangle $ abf $. The lines $ ab $ and $ ah $ are given, therefore $ bh $ is known, and the diameter of the circumference of the circumscribing circle from the doctrine of triangles. etc.

0029.jpg 15r 29 JS Mar 28, 2012 This folio provides a canon, or rule, for finding the square root of a quantity $ d + f $. Using the fundamental property established in the first line, the first term in the canon can be rewritten as the square root of $ \frac{bb + cc}{2} + \sqrt{\frac{(bb + cc)^2}{4} + \frac{4bc}{4}} $ $ = bb $. Similarly, the second term yields $ cc $. Thus the sum of the square roots yields $ b + c $, as required. A numerical example is worked at the bottom of the page. 0045.jpg 23r 45 Of ropes 6.) The sprit sayle hath clew lines like the topsayles but no bowlinges. & sheates but no tackes. hath also liftes as the other yardes.
0045.jpg 23r 45 Of ropes He hath garnets, one cometh from the middlest of the the arme, to a blocke towards the top of the boltsprit and so cometh downe by the boltsprit to the beake hed to be haled. His office to ease the lift & to help the sayle vere by a wind. So the other.
0045.jpg 23r 45 Of ropes The misons have but one lift which cometh from the top of the small end above, of the yard, & is reeved thourough a pully at the top of the mast & so cometh downe. one sheat, fast, at at the right angle, & cometh to a blocke in a bumkin without the ship asterne & so cometh in to be haled or thourough a blocke made fast aloft in the midst in aftermost part of the ship aloft & from there a little forward to be haled. His tacke is fast at the tayle (sharp angle aslo) & his other end is rope to be brought over to the wether side & there to be belayed to a kebble.
0045.jpg 23r 45 Of ropes The bowlinges are two ropes fast to the lower end of the yard (with a button of wood & an eye) and from there are reeved in two pullyes made fast to aftermost mayne shroude one on the one side & and the other on the other. the bowlinge is to be halyed when they set their mizon to go by a wind. When the sayle is furled, & the yard up, they being both hauled & belayed do steddy the yard in the middest of the ship.

0047.jpg 24r 47 Of ropes 10. Bowlinges (bowlines) Of the mayne bowling, is spliced fast about a pully having a shiner, & thourough that shiner passes a short rope having two deadmeneyes spliced at the two endes thereof, thourough whihch eyes come other small ropes making crow feet are spliced into side bolt rope of the mayne sayle; this parte from the pully is called the bridles; the other end of the bowling is reeved thourough a block made fast with a strap nere towards the foremaste on the top of the forecastle in the middest (of bredth) & from thence comes aft towards the mayne maste there to be haled. & is about kebble or some bitte. And thourough a shiner of the same blocke on the fore castle passes the bowling up the other side. And his use is when they go by a wind (the tackes being abord) & sheates haled aft) then to be haled tought & belayde; that the wether leech (side) be kept tought & and not to lift or shake in the wind.
0047.jpg 24r 47 Of ropes In like manner the fore bowlinge come thourough a blocke with a double shiner made fast about the middest of the bolt sprit & so comes thourough a blocke fast at the lower parte of the boltsprit (above the head beke) one one side (for on the other is an other) & so cometh into the the forecastle or up alofte there to be haled & belayed.
0047.jpg 24r 47 Of ropes The top sayle bowlings are reeved thourough two blockes sezed to the topmast stay & the mayne topsayle boweling once reeved agayne thourough two blockes about the rayles of the after part of the forecastle & so into the ship to be haled. but the foretopsayle bowlings are agayne thourough two pullyes fast towards the top of teh boltsprit (& so to the foretop then to be haled) or are reeved agayne agayne in two pullys at the lower part of the boltsprit & thence to the forecastle to be haled.

0049.jpg 25r 49 Of ropes The foresayle hath sheates and tackes made fast to the clewes in like manner as mayne sayle. One of the sheat is fastened at the middest of the maste or nere on the out side, & so reeved thourough the block with a strap at the clew & reeved thourough a shiner in the ships side nere the mayne maste & there is to be haled & belayed about kebble nere hand.
0049.jpg 25r 49 Of ropes The foretackes goe thourough two holes in a cleate (a peece of wood nayled to the bomkin (like a peece of a maste under the beake head fastened in bord) the small endes passing thourough are brought up on the contrary side of the maste throug orover the forecastle & there to be haled to bring the tacke abord; where the clew to the bomkin or as nere as it can.
0049.jpg 25r 49 Of ropes 7. Clew garnet of the maynesayle one end is fastened at the clew & the other reeved thourough a blocke fastened under the mayne yard towarde the maste on the same side or arme & so cometh downe to be haled to bring the clewes to the yard when the sayle is striken downe & then they use to furle up the sayle & ty it up with gaskets (yarn platted with nooses at the greater end) fastened with a rope yarn to a grummet (a nayle with a ring) driven into the yard & coming about the sayle they make it fast in a other grummet. They are many of them alongst the yard, but the middle two (or 4) being greater & longer than the rest are called breech gaskets; & when the sayle is to be let fall they order as many as they can & then cut the rope yarnes of the breech gaskets last of all & both together.
0049.jpg 25r 49 Of ropes 8. Martenet line, one end is fastened under the top & reeved thourough a double pully with 3 shiners (2 one way & one another) that is thourough the single shiner & so comes backe to a pully under the top & so goes downe by the foremost shroude there to be haled; thourough the double shiners of the pully come one on one side & the other on the other of the yard; at whose endes are dead men eyes. And thourough the holes of the dead men eyes are peeces of small line bothe endes of which line are spliced fast into the bolterope on the side & make crow feet. The use is by haling the martenet line to bring the sayle close to the yard at the yardarmes end & forwards In like sort also are the martenets of the foresayle.
0049.jpg 25r 49 Of ropes The luffe hooke, is a rope with a hooke having an eye or hole, thourough which a rope is reeved & spliced; whose use put the hooke into earing of the clew of the sayle if only the bonnet be on; or bonnet if drabble be on & the other end goeth thourough a hole in the ships side & there is haled in tought & belayed to helpe the tacke for feare of breaking. the mayne & foresayle only have this luffe hooke.

0057.jpg 29r 57 Ropes. One end of the Cable is to be brought ont at the Hawse and bent (mad fast) to the rynge of the Anchore, then the other end must be brought to the Bytte (two upright postes with a crosse peece of tymber bolted fast to beames alowe) and ther be belayde.
0057.jpg 29r 57 Ropes. then ther is a Bwye with a bwye rope, which rope is mad fast to the crosse of the Anchore, by which the anchore is to be wayd which a boat as occasion serveth.
0057.jpg 29r 57 Ropes. in letting fale the Anchore which hangeth in a stopper (as they cale it) a cock bylle ready to let fale, that when the master caleth they cast of the stoper) lett fale: then ther are many hands readye to over sette the fakes of the cable and followe it for feare of kinks, and one standeth by the stopper that when they crye stope he presently clapes the stopper about the cable and vers agayne as he is bydd the master as the shype cranes untyle shee be brought upe to a Bytter.
0057.jpg 29r 57 Ropes. The stopper is a strong rope about a fathome longe one end wherof is fast to the shypps syde (afore by the mange neer the Hawse.) at some rynge boult) or havinge a knott at one end is thrust thorowhe a hole in some stronge peece of tymber standinge conveniently neere the foresayd place, the other end is loose to be suddenly brought about the cable two or .3. tyms to stoppe it. And in wayinge they cast one the stopper upon the cable, and then cat it off at the Bytte & brynge the end to the capsten .
0057.jpg 29r 57 Ropes. When the Anchor is upe to the Hawser they have a great yron hooke to which a rope is fast which is caled a fyshhooke, they lett it downe and heech it about one of the flowkes of the Anchore, & bringe the Rope out to the end of a great peece of tymber thrust out over the syde (which they cale a Davitt) & then cry hale fish &c.
0057.jpg 29r 57 Ropes. Ther is one either syde the shypp before a peece of tymber fast to the shype syde standinge out with a shyner at the ende, caled the catte throwe which shyner they reeve a rope caled the catt rope one ende wher of they fasten to the rynge of the Anchore & hange this rope putinge out the cable at the hawse they bringe it upe, & then with takels they bringe the Anchor to the Bowe agayne. hale out &c.
0057.jpg 29r 57 Ropes. the greatest Anchor they cale the shoote Anchor the other Bowers ther is a smale Anchor with a longe cabled hawser which is caled a kedginge Anchor to warpe upon when occasion serveth.
0057.jpg 29r 57 Ropes. they lay out thsi smale Anchor with ther boat & bringinge the end aborde they heave the shipe to it & then lett drope another smale anchor under foote, & then lay out the kedginge anchor againe which they cale warpinge &c.
0057.jpg 29r 57 Ropes. this is used to gett out of a harbore when the wynd which bloweth would serve yf you were without the harbore, but they use it not but in fayre weather when the wynd doth not over blowe, for this lytle anchor would not then hould the shyppe.

The keele in a ship (100 t) of 12 yardes deep; 10 yardes broad The sterne post & stern are below as the keele but a loft the stern is thicker in & out (& otherwise also) it ends in a quadrant, & comes into the beake head as a stump. the beake hed is $ \frac{1}{5} $ or $\frac{1}{6} $ of the keele in length. The timbers (of 100 t) of the midship bend, are 7 inches in & out below & 8 inches brode, & a lofte about 3 inches every way. The wales are in thicknesse 5 yardes, & about 6 in bredth, the other are lesse the planke between is 3 inches & so down to the keele, upward they are thinner by degrees.
0059.jpg 30r 59 Notes. Upon the keel, the bendes are fastened with trennels; upon the floore timbers the keelson runns alonge, being bolted to the keel between the bendes. then on both sides the keelson is floored with plankes.

0077.jpg 39r 77 JS Aug 16, 2012 Captain Edmund Marlow (d. 1615) was described ten years after his death as 'an excellent man in the Art of Navigation, and all the Mathematicks'; see Purchas 1625, i, 444 No surviving copy of his Ars naupegica has been traced, and it is possible that it was never published but circulated only in manuscript. Notes taken out Captayne Edmund Marloe his booke intituled Ars Naupegica. or the art of ship building.
0077.jpg 39r 77 Notes taken out Captayne Edmund Marloe his booke intituled Ars Naupegica. or the art of ship building. The Easterling, Dues or Fleming, build floty ships by reason those countryes are subiect to flats & shoulds. And because they often bring them a ground they have much flat flore to rest them on. There sides also are upright, and are built so for burthen & small draught of water. And they beare sayle not so much for there sides, but by reason of the great weyght that lyeth below upon the flore, (being so broad & long). But these for the most part are evill conditioned ships in the sea: being subiect to rowle, tumble, & leape in a wrought sea; so that you must allwayes keep some sayle abrode.
0077.jpg 39r 77 Notes taken out Captayne Edmund Marloe his booke intituled Ars Naupegica. or the art of ship building. Contrarywise the Spaniard (not accustomed to bring his ships a ground) but allwayes to ride aflote, and also to trimme his ships upon the carine) buildeth sharpe deep ships, hanging of for the most part upon the nayle. As you may se by there Carbells. And there Caractes likewise for the most part flare much of aloft. Now these hold a better wind & are easier in a wrought sea, and will commonly hull well, & wether quoyle. But they draw much water & are not well to be brought a ground without good floring for feare they fall over.
0077.jpg 39r 77 Notes taken out Captayne Edmund Marloe his booke intituled Ars Naupegica. or the art of ship building. The Frenchmen are nearest to perfection in bearing style & going well, being neat moulded ships. But they are not commmonly so great in burthen as they loome for. They have long rakes & sharp forward on; and there decks steeve much forward. Where contrarywise, the Easterling & Dues have short upright rakes & bloof ships forwards on. Also there decks steeve or hung afterwardes on.
0077.jpg 39r 77 Notes taken out Captayne Edmund Marloe his booke intituled Ars Naupegica. or the art of ship building. But our English ships are intended to have such perfection, that (according to the intent of the builder) they hold burden with the Fleming; bearing with the Spaniard; going well with the French &c.
0077.jpg 39r 77 Notes taken out Captayne Edmund Marloe his booke intituled Ars Naupegica. or the art of ship building. Every nation aymeth at this to have there ships go well & stear well which proceedeth especially from the well weying of a ship fore & afte for the Runne & Tuck.
0077.jpg 39r 77 Notes taken out Captayne Edmund Marloe his booke intituled Ars Naupegica. or the art of ship building. These are the cheif propertyes of a ship in the sea. To go well; to stear well, & beare a good sayle. As for the Burthen that belongeth to the owners profit, which some to much affecting hath made us to have so many furred ships.

0081.jpg 41r 81 Notes. It is knowne by experience that a ship whose depth. 10, foote bredth. 20 length 50 by the keele is of burden a 100 tonne.
0081.jpg 41r 81 Notes. M. Baker makes this rule & findes it little more or lesse than the truth otherwise tried: he makes a solid nomber of 10. 20. & 50; & then devides it by a hundred; the quotient is the tonnes of burden; the sayd length depth & bredth must be in feete for this rule.
0081.jpg 41r 81 Notes. ffor tonne & tonnage of the Kinges ships he multiplyes as before but devides by 70. & the quotient is counted her tonnage. By these rules tonnage of shipps is measured for the King.
0081.jpg 41r 81 Notes. Tonne & tonnage is what a ship doth carry of ordinaure mastes sayles & yardes, together with that which she carry in hold: &c.
0081.jpg 41r 81 Notes. Ths solid nomber of 10. 20. 50. is: 10,000. And so many solide feet is that parallelepiped. Now it semeth to me that that parallelepipied is to the bulke of the ship as 3 to 1. or nere. for devide the nomber by 3 & then the bulke bulke of the hsip is, 3,333. in feet. then every solide foot holding 64 pound of water; I multiply it by 64 and it amounteth to in pounds, 213, 312. which devided by .2240. yieldeth 95, tonne. 20 times 112 being the tonne. but by 2000, yieldeth 106. tonne. reckoning 20 times 100, only for the tonne. And so M Bakers rule happeneth to be the meane.
0081.jpg 41r 81 Notes. In deviding it by 70, the tonnage it is 143 tonnes. That tonne being 2,240 maketh the above sayd parall- epiped to be just double to the bulke. Therefore 5000 multiplied by 64 maketh 320,000 & devided by 2240. yieldeth 143.

Therefore in the parallell for the 23 bend in the playne of bredth & length is to be taken the narrowing & bredth a loft for the fashion peece. to which narrowing, $ ee $ is æquall; so that $ ke $ is the bredth a lofte. 0087.jpg 44r 87 Notes. or observations. of the midship bend. or, the mould. In making of the mould from the flat floore is specially to be considered the hanging of of the side from $ b $ to $ d $, or $ e $. for which they have no certayne rule but judgement by the ey. these thinges being considered; the holding of goods, the sayling, & bearing. The greater the breadth is at the wrong heads the more they carry, in weyght, but hindreth there going. if $ cd $ be to round shee is subiect to rouling. &c.
0087.jpg 44r 87 Notes. or observations. of the midship bend. or, the mould. the line $ bm $ extended be double to $ ak $ let that be a semidiameter. of an elipse which must come by $ d $) then seke out the poynt $ m $ to make $ bc $ an arke to go fayne upon the elipsis. then by assay seek the center $ o $ to make an arke to touch the arke $ bc $ & come by $ d $. then in the line $ ek $, take $ ne $ half or lesse then $ \frac{1}{2} $ of $ ke $ but see that in the successe it also be shorter then the depth of fashion peece as above. for marchants ships let the diameter of the sayd elipsis be a quarter lesse or there abouts, becasue the lesse the diameter is, the fuller she is be low at the wrong heds.

And these two wayes M Marlow useth for to consider of his mould in intention which M Baker approveth.

0234.jpg 117v 234 JS Aug 5, 2012 This important letter to Harriot from Nathaniel Torporley foretells Torporley's first meeting with François Viète, the 'French Apollon'. Unfortunately, although the letter is marked '16 Sept', no year is given. However, it must have been written before Viète's death in 1603. For further arguments about the dating, see below. Later accounts of Torporley described him as 'amanusenis' or perhaps secretary to Viète. It seems, therefore, that, as suggested by this letter, Torporley did indeed stay for a few weeks or months in Paris, during which time he was in regular contact with Viète, perhaps copying or transcribing his mansucripts. This would explain the presence of a sheet in Harriot's mansucripts marked 'A problem of Viète from Torporley'. More importantly, it would explain Harriot's access to all the works of Viète, of which only a few copies were printed and which were not easily available even in France. Harriot began working his way systematically through Viète's Zeteticorum libri quinque on 29 August 1600 (see Add MS 6782 f. 481 ). This suggests either that Torporley had already returend to England by then, bringing with him copies of Viète's books, or that he had them sent to Harriot from Paris. The letter on this page, dated 16 September, must therefore have been written earlier, perhaps the previous year, 1599. Torporley's description of Viète as the French Apollon presumably derives from the latter's Apollonius Gallus, published in Paris in 1600, but perhaps a copy of it, or at least its title, was already known to Torporley some months beforehand. It is difficult otherwise to reconcile the September date of Torporley's letter with the August date of Harriot's notes.
0234.jpg 117v 234 Good Mr. Hariots, beinge certayne how welcome to you newes of discoveries wilbe; I sende you these briefe commendations from the new founde Tropike of Paris. For such, by my farre travaile I fynde the greatest obliquitie of my variable Zodiake; which, by the Tables of equall motion, ought ot have extended to the clyme Diako And thus I geve yo to understande (in some voluntarie obscuritie, and shaminge in playne termes to come in what ) the summe of my fortunes synce my departure from London. You may in what continuall motion I have bene, that have sene Grave, Calais, Amiens, & and am now at Paris retrograde, & . And even my stile (me thinkes) discovers my exchaunge agayne of Mars for the muses; the rather now, because I am gathering up my ruined wittes, the better to encounter that French Apollon: if it fortune that either his courtsie or my bouldness effecte our conference; tomorrow beinge the daye, when if I am appoynted his Printer, as little Zacheus to climbe the tree, to gayne a viewe of that renouwned Analist. What after followes presence I hope shortly to relate, yet resolved to consume some weekes heare, so longe it maye be tyll I maye heare agayne out of Englande, I have for you, if not out of season, Sim: S his owne plotte of the laste siege of Grave, which, because I thinke maye be common ynough with you ere now, I therefore make no earnest haste to sende it, but will wait some beafore being meane while commending you to your deserved good fortunes, & my in all due respectes to your continued goodwill, I take my leave as Yours ever in true fidelitie Nath. Torporley 16 Sept: English

0300.jpg 150v 300 mschemmel 04.10.2013 The page is part of Harriot's calculation of ranges and his search for the projection angle of maximum range in the context of the inclined-plane conception of projectile motion, see (Schemmel 2008, Section 8.3). Harriot develops a scheme for the determination of a candidate angle of maximum range and notes the result following from calculations on f. 149v. The fundamental idea is that the angle of maximum range is given by that angle for which the intersection of the parabolic trajectory with its largest diameter lies on the line of the horizon. The corresponding range is determined on f. 162v. For an explanation of the geometrical terms used by Harriot and of his procedure for calculating the angle, see Schemmel 2008, 187-90. 10)

0316.jpg 158v 316 mschemmel 02.10.2013 The page is part of Harriot's calculation of ranges and his search for the projection angle of maximum range in the context of the inclined-plane conception of projectile motion, see (Schemmel 2008, Section 8.3). (According to this conception, projectile motion is composed of a decelerated motion in the oblique direction of the shot, and an accelerated motion of vertical fall. The dependence of the oblique motion on the angle of projection corresponds to that of a motion along an inclined plane on the angle of inclination.) Harriot calculates the range of a shot at 45° elevation, which in many places of the contemporary literature on gunnery is assumed to be the angle of maximum range, see, e.g., (Bourne 1587, 39). His result is 88,889 units of length. 6.) For oblique motions. The randon of 45°.

0969.jpg 485r 969 1. Some remembrances of taking altitude of sonne by the Astrolabe and Sea Rings.
0969.jpg 485r 969 1. Some remembrances of taking altitude of sonne by the Astrolabe and Sea Rings. There are three instruments used at sea for taking of altitude, the Astrolabe, The ring, & the staffe. The Astolabe hath here most ancient & is used commonly & only for the sonne; and serveth the seamans turne most specially when the sonne is becuase then they find the staffe very uncertayne. And when the sea is wrought it is very hard to make any observation by it also; because of his agitation & unquiet guaging.
0969.jpg 485r 969 1. Some remembrances of taking altitude of sonne by the Astrolabe and Sea Rings. But howsoever when there is need you must do as well as you may. and therefore when you have your Astrolabe guaging as quietly as the time will permit with his side toward the sonne according to the usual order, you are to fit the Judex by moving it so long up & downe till the former shine thourough the holes of both the sights at the same time. Or you finding by reason of his agitation that the sonne will not passe iustly thourough the lower sights but be sometme higher & sometime lower. where you finde the lyst of the syghts now as much over as under: then your Judex standeth as precisely as if the Astrolabe had hong quietly; & sheweth the true altitude of the center of the sonne.
0969.jpg 485r 969 1. Some remembrances of taking altitude of sonne by the Astrolabe and Sea Rings. But if you doubt of the true guaging of the AStrolabe, you may move your Judex quickly to the same signe on the other side & hold it towards the sonne. If you find the sonne shine thourough as before your Astrolabe hangeth well. Otherwise you are also to move Judex, till you have also the altitude on that side. Which had, compare with the other & note the difference. The half of that difference added to the lesse altitude or detract from the greater; And you have the altitude of the sonne as exacte as if your Astrolabe had hung truly upright.
0969.jpg 485r 969 1. Some remembrances of taking altitude of sonne by the Astrolabe and Sea Rings. The other instrument called is of late yeares in great use with the Portingalls & Spaniards, The making whereof & use they had about 40 yeares of a country man of their owne a learned mathematician called Petrus Nonius who also hath written of the arte of Navigating as well in Latin as in Spanish. And is only for taking the altitude of the sonne as the Astrolabe. but for ease & space it much excelleth it as also for exactnesse. for the degrees are as large agayne as in an Astrolabe of the same signes. And in the use, there is no troublesome moving up & downe any Judex as in an Astrolabe; but it guaging as the Astrolabe, & that side which hath a small pole bing holden towards the sonne; the light passing thourough sheweth upon the degrees noted within the ring the altitude of the sonne you desire. you are to note that the middle of the light be it round or long is your true marke. And if the light play by reason of his unquiet hanging; then the middle of the play is the hight. This instrument is continued together for your use the last viadge with the Astrolabe , And upon your returne it was geven to your servant Cap. Whidden, who now also hath it redy for your use. By our last practice I found much lighter then it ought to be, which is a fault also in all the Astrolabes I have seene. By reason of your speedy setting forth it cnnot more be remedied; but is to be used as conveni-
0970.jpg 485v 970
0970.jpg 485v 970 niently as it may & the inconvenience I will there fore shall be by the staffe in the next charte.
0971.jpg 486r 971 1. 2. Of taking of altitudes of the sonne or any starre by the corsse staffe with more exactness then hath ben used heretofore.
0971.jpg 486r 971 1. 2. Of taking of altitudes of the sonne or any starre by the corsse staffe with more exactness then hath ben used heretofore. The staffe is the other instrument well knowne & used at sea especially of starres. But as is hath ben used heretofore the seamasters commit great errors then sometimes they are aware of from which errors if it be purged it is then of more apte & certayne use also for the sonne then ether the Astrolabe or Ring which I meane in this chapter to shew.
0971.jpg 486r 971 1. 2. Of taking of altitudes of the sonne or any starre by the corsse staffe with more exactness then hath ben used heretofore. The staffe is devided with presuppose that the end thereof in should stand in the center of the sight. And though that cannot be performed, yet the common practiser thinketh there is little errour in putting of it close under ey they behold withall: some on the utmost corner of that ey: some on the cheke bone: some on one side of the bridge of the nose. All which placinges to some eyes, sometimes in some manner of observinges, may prove true; & for the utmost corner of the ey to some eyes, alwayes.
0971.jpg 486r 971 1. 2. Of taking of altitudes of the sonne or any starre by the corsse staffe with more exactness then hath ben used heretofore. But all men that have not a seat for the staffe iust agaynst the center of the sight, as most men have not, must needs find a full altitude still & in great altitudes the errour wilbe so as that it cannot be borne withall, without artificiall correction; meaning allowance or abatement, which hitherto have not ben made. And wher the seamen have espied it ether by great difference from there recconings, or comparison with there Astrolabe; for such great altitudes they geve over the staffe.
0971.jpg 486r 971 1. 2. Of taking of altitudes of the sonne or any starre by the corsse staffe with more exactness then hath ben used heretofore. How this errour may be knowne & reformed I have demonstrated & taught 11 yeares past in my booke called Arcticon. Now only I will remember unto you out of the same, that which I shewed you sometime to fore & sufficient for your use.
0971.jpg 486r 971 1. 2. Of taking of altitudes of the sonne or any starre by the corsse staffe with more exactness then hath ben used heretofore. The best place to set the end of your staffe is the utmost corner of the seat of that ey which you mind to behold withall. because that place is firme & certayne without offense to the eye. And then how farre the end of staffe doth stand the center of your sight according as it hath ben already observed by a staffe I have for the purpose: I have marked in a spare place of both your staves nere the note of 90 degrees. And the same quantity I have found to be in Cap. Whiddous; in Douglas the masters; & many more else, as in yours & mine. The which quantity hereafter for brevity & order sake according to the nature of the thing I call the excentricity of the staffe.
0971.jpg 486r 971 1. 2. Of taking of altitudes of the sonne or any starre by the corsse staffe with more exactness then hath ben used heretofore. The use of it is this: when you have according to the usuall manner taken the sight of the sonne or starre & noted the place where the crosee stand you are to consider what sight that wilbe which is further from the ey by the quantity of the excentricity which you may knowe by the helpe of a payre of compasses, & doth alwayes make it lesse then the former. And that sight or altitude is as true as if the end of your staffe did stand in the center of your sight.
0972.jpg 486v 972
0973.jpg 487r 973 2.
0973.jpg 487r 973 2. or else you may note the altitude as you find it by the place of the crosse at first; & after set downe so much in degrees or minutes as from the place of the crosse answereth to the quantity of the excentricity, which hereafter is called the parallaxis of the staffe; to remayne to be abated with some other things as shalbe taught after.
0973.jpg 487r 973 2. If to the prime end of the staffe that is to say the end which is next the eye nere ioyned a peece of wood of the length of the excentricity the use wold now be somewhat reddier for your owne ey without removing the crosse any otherwise then in the observation, or further consideration of parallaxis.
0973.jpg 487r 973 2. There is yet an other thing to be noted in observing of altitude by the staffe. The seamen use comonly to leave the horison open in , which in deed were good if they know how much, but because of the uncertayne coniecture they may make greater greater error then is fit to be permitted. They have the practice by tradition from one to the other. The reason thereof they told none in there writings, nether being demanded to they answere any otherwise then that not doing so, the altitude wold not be true, nor agree with the Astrolabe. Which without doubt have ben found by comparing the staffe & the Astrolabe to gether.
0973.jpg 487r 973 2. By truth of demonstration which I have uttered in my Arcticon, which here for brevity sake I omit. I have proved that the ey being above the levell of the water at sea, doth see more then half the heavens. And therefore from the zenith or highest poynt above our heads to the apparent horizon is more then 90 degrees. And that surplus is the greater, according as the ey is above the levell of the water. And therefore any high that is taken by the staffe close, because it hath respecte to the visible horizon, is greater then from the true horizon of the world.
0973.jpg 487r 973 2. Yet notwithstanding it is the surest way in using the staffe to take the altitude close from the Horizon, because of the uncertayen opening that the Mariners leave. Which altitude without respecte of parallaxis I call the Apparent altitude. And then the surplus with the parallaxis together are to be abated to make the true altitude desired.
0973.jpg 487r 973 2. The quantity of which surplus I have set downe in a litle speciall table here following according to the sondry distances of the ey from the levell of the water.
0973.jpg 487r 973 2. As when the ey is one pase that is 5 foote from the levell of the water, then the abatement is $ 3' $. when 2 pases then $ 4' $ & so forth as in the table. Upon the poope of a tall ship the hight of the ey comonly is 4 or 5 pases & then your abatement is $ 5' $ or $ 6' $. Upon the decke in the waste $ 5' $. & at the cheynes $ 4' $ wilbe the abatement, which by triall with the load & line you may find.
0973.jpg 487r 973 2. And this you ought generally to note that whensoever you observe with the staffe, you make good your high, iust when your ship is on the top of the surge of sea, otherwise you may err.
0974.jpg 487v 974
0975.jpg 488r 975 3.
0975.jpg 488r 975 3. Hight of the ey above the water in pases.
0975.jpg 488r 975 3. Surplus of the Horizon in minuts.
0975.jpg 488r 975 3. those thinges being regarded which I have specifyed concerning the staffe: you may henceforward make as true observations as need to be: the starre or sonne being of any hight. the seamaster durst not to trust to the altitude of the sonne or starre being 60 degrees & upward. because of the difference from the Astrolabe, imputing the error to the uncertenty in beholding; when as in deed they know not the abatement I before spake of. the parallaxis & surplus & that is the cause of there experimental opening of Horizon. And although the error about 30 degrees no great matter of some $ 10' $ or there aboute, yet in the hight of 60 & upward it amounteth to . In starres of the largest size the error was the lesse; but now by reason of the former correction, the longer & shorter sorte will agree.
0975.jpg 488r 975 3. ffor taking the sonnes high also by the staffe I thinke good also to prescribe uncertenty, & to remember unto you the meanes for it may be done without offense to the ey.
0975.jpg 488r 975 3. Those men that set a glasse at the end of there staffe or end of the crosse do error. It is manifest without any further reason by a common experiment of looking thorugh glasse windows, that the thinges seene thourough, are seen distorted, out of there places, by reason of refraction of the visuall beames in the arte of optickes demonstratively appro- ved. Therefore such meanes I wish to be left.
0975.jpg 488r 975 3. The best way that I can præscribe, which some do also use, is to take the high of the upper edge of the sonne, hiding the whole body with the breadth of the crosse: And when you have don, to abate 16 minuts; because the diameter or breadth of the sonne is $ 32' $. and then you have the hight of the center of the sonne which you ought to have.
0976.jpg 488v 976
0977.jpg 489r 977 4.
0977.jpg 489r 977 4. And this you may do without offendinge the ey, if you be wary. In the beginning of your observation first hide the sonne with the crosse & so keep him hidden with the orderly moving of your body & hand answerable to the surge of the sea, & you bring him downe by litle & litle till you se only the edge of the sonne; & if you see the other end of the crosse upon quick sight close with the Horizon, it is well. Otherwise you must pull to or put from the crosse untill you find that agreement.
0977.jpg 489r 977 4. The summe of all in taking altitudes by the staffe is this. ffirst take the altitude close from the Horizon & that is called the Apparent altitude. ffrom it abate two thinges that is the parallaxis of the staffe & the surplus of the Horizon. The remaynder is the true hight of the starre.
0977.jpg 489r 977 4. But if you take the higher edge of the sonne you must abate 16 minuts more & you have the true altitude desired.
0977.jpg 489r 977 4. If absolute exacteness were to be required then it is yet to be addded to the sonne two thinges, that is to say his parallaxis of altitude, & angle of refraction caused by the highest superficies of the ayre: And to the altitude of the starre only the angle of refraction. but because in your voyadge they amount not ether one or both to 3 minuts , I leave them for other place & time to be uttered.

0981.jpg 491r 981 How to know your course to sayle to any place assigned; & in sayling to make true recconing where you are at any time; & how farre from any place desired.
0981.jpg 491r 981 How to know your course to sayle to any place assigned; & in sayling to make true recconing where you are at any time; & how farre from any place desired. In the art of Navigation it is præsupposed that plottes & sea chartes have the costes, Islands and other places in them described & situated proportionally and answerable to those they represent. as well for true course & distance as magnitude & forme. So that those places that have one latitude or altitude of the pole, stand in a true east & west course; & those that one meridian, stand in a North & south course; & so per consequence all the other meane courses in the chartes signified, must be understoode to be according & answerable to the true compasse, & not to the common or any compasse else that have variation. But if the compasse vary; by recconing in sayling, allowance or abatement is to be made that the true course may be knowne; else shall you be sure to misse your poste or place desired.
0981.jpg 491r 981 How to know your course to sayle to any place assigned; & in sayling to make true recconing where you are at any time; & how farre from any place desired. And if in chartes such respects be not had; but that places be set downe by the common compasse, or other compasses as they be found, respect to there variation; then where the compasses do vary, there do places stand out of there true latitudes ; & in navigation, elevations of the poles for correcting your dead reckonings would stand you in no steed. Neither could any navigaton be performed, but only on such courses as the planes were first found by. For upon other courses according as your deviation is greater or lesse so much should you sayle of your purpose wether you considered therein variation or not; if the compasse in courses have a greater or lesse variation then in the courses originall.

1071.jpg 536r 1071 JS Mar 28, 2012 This is a key page in which Harriot sets out his calculations of population under the conditions set out in Add MS 6782 f. 31v , and Add MS 6788 f. 537 , namely, that each male–female pair gives birth to a child each year, alternately male and female, and that those children begin to reproduce after 20 years. All survive indefinitely. Harriot gives no verbal explanation of the calculations, and there are only a few surviving rough diagrams like that in Add MS 6788 f. 554 . Take the calculations for 30 years as an example. Now there are 15 males born to the original couple; these are marked 'a'. Meanwhile, the 5 oldest males have begun to reproduce, giving birth to 5 + 4 + 3 + 2 + 1 = 15 male children. This sum can be calculated by the rule $ \frac{n(n + 1)}{2} $, giving the $ n $th triangular number. This calculation is marked 'b'. The calculations for subsequent years follow a similar pattern. At 50 years, the second generation, measured by triangular numbers, has begun to reproduce. The third generation is therefore measured by sums of triangular numbers, that is, pyramidal numbers, calculated by the rule $ \frac{n(n + 1)(n + 2)}{6} $. This calculations is marked 'c'. And so on.
